{"title_page": "Studio 58", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Studio 58\n|native_name     =\n|latin_name      =\n|former_names    = Arts program, Vancouver City College (1965 - 1970)\n|image           = [[File:Studio_58_Logo.jpg|250px]]\n|motto           = \n|established     = {{Start date|1965}}\n|type            = [[Public university|Public]]\n|endowment       =\n|staff           = 5\n|faculty         = 18\n|president       = \n|provost         =\n|principal       = \n|rector          =\n|chancellor      =\n|vice_chancellor =\n|dean            = \n|head_label      = Artistic Director\n|head            = Kathryn Shaw\n|students        = Approx. 76\n|undergrad       = \n|postgrad        = \n|doctoral        = \n|city            = [[Vancouver]]\n|province        = [[British Columbia]]\n|country         = [[Canada]]\n|coor            = {{Coord|49|13|30|N|123|6|30|W|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n|campus          = [[Vancouver]] ([[urban area|Urban]])\n|free_label      =\n|free            =\n|colours         = {{color box|Black}} [[Black (color)|Black]]<br/>{{color box|#FFFFFF}} [[White]] \n|athletics       = \n|nickname        = Studio\n|mascot          = \n|affiliations    = [[Association of Canadian Community Colleges|ACCC]], [[Canadian Bureau for International Education|CBIE]], [[Canadian University Press|CUP]]\n|website         = http://www.langara.bc.ca/studio-58/\n|logo            = Clip image002 0001.png\n}}\n\n'''Studio 58''' is a professional [[Drama school|theatre training school]] in [[Vancouver]], [[Canada]]. A part of [[Langara College]]'s [[Theatre arts|Theatre Arts]] Program, the school offers a three-year program for acting students and a two-year program for production students. A [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] is offered with an additional year of study through a partnership with [[Capilano University]]. It is distinguished as one of the top theatre schools in Canada and the only conservatory-style theatre training program in [[Western Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/carmen-aguirre|title=Carmen Aguirre|author=Paula Jessop|publisher=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ent-nts.ca/journal/j20p10_teaching.htm|title=The Stagecraft Legacy: Teaching Theatre in Canada 1960-2000|date=2002|author=Patrick McDonagh|publisher=[[National Theatre School of Canada]]|access-date=2012-12-31|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116004750/http://www.ent-nts.ca/journal/j20p10_teaching.htm|archive-date=2013-01-16|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe school auditions hundreds of people across Canada but only sixteen students are accepted per semester. The school has around 72 students for both its three-year acting program and two-year production program. Studio 58 operates a small theatre and presents 4 full-length productions annually as well as a smaller presentation of a student created show in a separate space. Professional directors and designers are hired to work on each production, and occasionally guest performing artists. Studio 58 productions are open to the public and reviewed by the Vancouver media.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straight.com/arts/studio-58s-production-comedy-errors-fireworks|title=Studio 58's production of The Comedy of Errors is like fireworks|date=31 January 2011|author=Colin Thomas|publisher=[[The Georgia Straight]]|accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe school was founded in 1965 as a small [[theatre arts]] course first held on the King Edward Campus of Vancouver City College, now [[Vancouver Community College]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SzpmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=H4sNAAAAIBAJ&pg=3111,4789620&dq=studio-58+vancouver&hl=en|publisher=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|title= Intelligent restraint marks student acting|date= 12 April 1973|author=Christopher Dafoe|accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref> Led under the direction of [[Antony Holland]] the course grew into a full program. In 1970, the program moved to new facilities on the Langara Campus and became known as Studio 58, named after the room number of the original theatre space.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/canada/vancouver/entertainment-nightlife/other/studio-58|title=Studio 58|publisher=[[Lonely Planet]]|accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref> The theatre program has subsequently moved into new buildings but the name remains to this day.\n\nIn 1985, Holland stepped down as the [[Artistic Director]] and [[Kathryn Shaw]] stepped into the role. The same year, Jane Heyman moved into the newly formed position as Associated Director until 2005. She was replaced by David Hudgins, a graduate of the program.\n\nDevelopment in 2012 led to a partnership of theatre programs in Vancouver where a Bachelor of Fine Arts is offered graduates through an additional year of study at Capilano University.\n\n==Notable staff==\n\n* [[Aaron Bushkowsky]] - [[Playwriting]]\n* [[Kathryn Shaw]] - Artistic Director; Acting\n* [[Elizabeth Ball]] - Former Artistic Director, [[Carousel Theatre]] \n* [[Jay Brazeau]] - Actor\n* [[Christopher Gaze]] - Artistic Director, [[Bard on the Beach]]\n* [[Chris McGregor]]- Artistic Director,  Axis Theatre Company\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Scott Bellis]] - Actor, Director\n* [[Kim Collier]] - Siminovitch Prize Winning Director\n* [[Brian Drummond]] - Actor\n* [[Bob Frazer]] - Actor\n* [[Carmen Aguirre]] - Actor, Director, Writer\n* [[Lara Gilchrist]] - Actress<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kissinger|first1=Michael|title=Invisible woman gives geeky teenagers, German lesbians a voice|work=Vancouver Courier|page=39|publisher=Postmedia|date=March 2, 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Kevin Kerr (actor)|Kevin Kerr]] - Playwright\n* [[Jonathan Lachlan-Stewart]] - Actor\n* [[Dean Paul Gibson]] - Actor, Director\n* Nicole LeVasseur - Actor\n* [[Kevin Loring]] - Actor, Playwright\n* [[John Mann (musician)|John Mann]] - actor, musician\n* [[Kevin McNulty (actor)|Kevin McNulty]] - Actor\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Scott McNeil]] - Actor\n* [[Robert McQueen (director)|Robert McQueen]] - Director\n* [[Colin Mochrie]] - Actor, [[Whose Line Is It Anyway? (UK TV series)|Whose Line Is It Anyway?]]\n* [[Kris Nelson (producer)|Kris Nelson]] - Producer\n* [[Ty Olsson]] - Actor\n* [[David Richmond-Peck]] - Actor\n* [[Craig Veroni]] - Actor\n* [[Jonathon Young]] - Actor\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.langara.bc.ca/studio58/ Studio 58 Website] Langara College\n\n[[Category:Education in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Drama schools in Canada]]\n[[Category:Theatre companies in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Performing arts in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Langara College]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Studio 58\n|native_name     =\n|latin_name      =\n|former_names    = Arts program, Vancouver City College (1965 - 1970)\n|image           = [[File:Studio_58_Logo.jpg|250px]]\n|motto           = \n|established     = {{Start date|1965}}\n|type            = [[Public university|Public]]\n|endowment       =\n|staff           = 5\n|faculty         = 18\n|president       = \n|provost         =\n|principal       = \n|rector          =\n|chancellor      =\n|vice_chancellor =\n|dean            = \n|head_label      = Artistic Director\n|head            = Kathryn Shaw\n|students        = Approx. 76\n|undergrad       = \n|postgrad        = \n|doctoral        = \n|city            = [[Vancouver]]\n|province        = [[British Columbia]]\n|country         = [[Canada]]\n|coor            = {{Coord|49|13|30|N|123|6|30|W|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n|campus          = [[Vancouver]] ([[urban area|Urban]])\n|free_label      =\n|free            =\n|colours         = {{color box|Black}} [[Black (color)|Black]]<br/>{{color box|#FFFFFF}} [[White]] \n|athletics       = \n|nickname        = Studio\n|mascot          = \n|affiliations    = [[Association of Canadian Community Colleges|ACCC]], [[Canadian Bureau for International Education|CBIE]], [[Canadian University Press|CUP]]\n|website         = http://www.langara.bc.ca/studio-58/\n|logo            = Clip image002 0001.png\n}}\n\n'''Studio 58''' is a professional [[Drama school|theatre training school]] in [[Vancouver]], [[Canada]]. A part of [[Langara College]]'s [[Theatre arts|Theatre Arts]] Program, the school offers a three-year program for acting students and a two-year program for production students. A [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] is offered with an additional year of study through a partnership with [[Capilano University]]. It is distinguished as one of the top theatre schools in Canada and the only conservatory-style theatre training program in [[Western Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/carmen-aguirre|title=Carmen Aguirre|author=Paula Jessop|publisher=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ent-nts.ca/journal/j20p10_teaching.htm|title=The Stagecraft Legacy: Teaching Theatre in Canada 1960-2000|date=2002|author=Patrick McDonagh|publisher=[[National Theatre School of Canada]]|access-date=2012-12-31|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116004750/http://www.ent-nts.ca/journal/j20p10_teaching.htm|archive-date=2013-01-16|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe school auditions hundreds of people across Canada but only sixteen students are accepted per semester. The school has around 72 students for both its three-year acting program and two-year production program. Studio 58 operates a small theatre and presents 4 full-length productions annually as well as a smaller presentation of a student created show in a separate space. Professional directors and designers are hired to work on each production, and occasionally guest performing artists. Studio 58 productions are open to the public and reviewed by the Vancouver media.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straight.com/arts/studio-58s-production-comedy-errors-fireworks|title=Studio 58's production of The Comedy of Errors is like fireworks|date=31 January 2011|author=Colin Thomas|publisher=[[The Georgia Straight]]|accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe school was founded in 1965 as a small [[theatre arts]] course first held on the King Edward Campus of Vancouver City College, now [[Vancouver Community College]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SzpmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=H4sNAAAAIBAJ&pg=3111,4789620&dq=studio-58+vancouver&hl=en|publisher=[[The Vancouver Sun]]|title= Intelligent restraint marks student acting|date= 12 April 1973|author=Christopher Dafoe|accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref> Led under the direction of [[Antony Holland]] the course grew into a full program. In 1970, the program moved to new facilities on the Langara Campus and became known as Studio 58, named after the room number of the original theatre space.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/canada/vancouver/entertainment-nightlife/other/studio-58|title=Studio 58|publisher=[[Lonely Planet]]|accessdate=2012-12-31}}</ref> The theatre program has subsequently moved into new buildings but the name remains to this day.\n\nIn 1985, Holland stepped down as the [[Artistic Director]] and [[Kathryn Shaw]] stepped into the role. The same year, Jane Heyman moved into the newly formed position as Associated Director until 2005. She was replaced by David Hudgins, a graduate of the program.\n\nDevelopment in 2012 led to a partnership of theatre programs in Vancouver where a Bachelor of Fine Arts is offered graduates through an additional year of study at Capilano University.\n\n==Notable staff==\n\n* [[Aaron Bushkowsky]] - [[Playwriting]]\n* [[Kathryn Shaw]] - Artistic Director; Acting\n* [[Elizabeth Ball]] - Former Artistic Director, [[Carousel Theatre]] \n* [[Jay Brazeau]] - Actor\n* [[Christopher Gaze]] - Artistic Director, [[Bard on the Beach]]\n* [[Chris McGregor]]- Artistic Director,  Axis Theatre Company\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Scott Bellis]] - Actor, Director\n* [[Kim Collier]] - Siminovitch Prize Winning Director\n* [[Brian Drummond]] - Actor\n* [[Bob Frazer]] - Actor\n* [[Carmen Aguirre]] - Actor, Director, Writer\n* [[Lara Gilchrist]] - Actress<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kissinger|first1=Michael|title=Invisible woman gives geeky teenagers, German lesbians a voice|work=Vancouver Courier|page=39|publisher=Postmedia|date=March 2, 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Kevin Kerr (actor)|Kevin Kerr]] - Playwright\n* [[Jonathan Lachlan-Stewart]] - Actor\n* [[Dean Paul Gibson]] - Actor, Director\n* [[John Mann (musician)|John Mann]] - actor, musician\n* [[Kevin McNulty (actor)|Kevin McNulty]] - Actor\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Scott McNeil]] - Actor\n* [[Robert McQueen]] - Director\n* [[Colin Mochrie]] - Actor, [[Whose Line Is It Anyway? (UK TV series)|Whose Line Is It Anyway?]]\n* [[Ty Olsson]] - Actor\n* [[David Richmond-Peck]] - Actor\n* [[Craig Veroni]] - Actor\n* [[Jonathon Young]] - Actor\n* [[Kevin Loring]] - Actor, Playwright\n* [[Kris Nelson]] - Producer\n* Nicole LeVasseur - Actor\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.langara.bc.ca/studio58/ Studio 58 Website] Langara College\n\n[[Category:Education in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Drama schools in Canada]]\n[[Category:Theatre companies in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Performing arts in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Langara College]]\n", "name_user": "Zanimum", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable alumni", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Studio_58"}
