|authorlink=Will Hermes}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/apr/30/entertainment/ca-32479 |title=Old 97's, '20 Fight Songs,' Elektra |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 30, 1999 |accessdate=October 5, 2016 |last=Weingarten |first=Marc}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 4.0/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/o/old-97s/fight-songs.shtml |title=Old 97's: Fight Songs |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=February 16, 2012 |last=Lieberman |first=Neil |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000816183239/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/o/old-97s/fight-songs.shtml |archivedate=August 16, 2000 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/old97s/albums/album/87225/review/5941216/fight_songs |title=Old 97's: Fight Songs |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=May 27, 1999 |accessdate=February 16, 2012 |last=Moon |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Moon |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930212115/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/old97s/albums/album/87225/review/5941216/fight_songs |archivedate=September 30, 2007}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Old 97's |last=Harris |first=Keith |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |year=2004 |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |edition=4th |editor1-last=Brackett |editor1-first=Nathan |editor2-last=Hoard |editor2-first=Christian |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/602 602\u201303] }}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = 7/10<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xY9xO99TYMYC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA144 |title=Old 97's: Fight Songs |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |volume=15 |issue=6 |date=April 30, 1999 |accessdate=October 5, 2016 |last=Schone |first=Mark |page=144}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev10Score = A<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv599-99.php |title=Consumer Guide |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=May 18, 1999 |accessdate=October 5, 2016 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Fight Songs''''' is the fourth studio [[album]] by [[United States|American]] [[alternative country]] band [[Old 97's]], first released on April 27, [[1999 in music|1999]]. It features the song \"Murder (Or a Heart Attack)\", which was ranked #176 on ''[[Blender Magazine|Blender]]'' magazine's list of \"500 Greatest Songs From 1980-2005.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cs.ubc.ca/~davet/music/list/Best5.html |title=Blender Magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe group's second record on [[Elektra Records]], ''Fight Songs'' is more slick and pop-oriented than the group's previous efforts, a trend continued on 2001's ''[[Satellite Rides]]''. The song \"Crash on the Barrelhead\" is rumored to be targeted at alt-country rival, [[Ryan Adams]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://niche-appeal.com/beating-up-on-ryan-adams-an-emerging-songwriting-genre/|title=Dissing Ryan Adams: An Emerging Songwriting Genre|last=Falatko|first=Daniel|date=29 March 2018|website=Niche Apparel}}</ref> while \"Murder&nbsp;...\" was inspired by a cat owned by singer Miller's roommate in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/old-97-s-hid-a-missing-cat-saga-in-a-love-song-1798282609|title=Old 97s Hid A Missing Cat Sage in a Love Song|last=Browning|first=Laura|date=4 August 2015|website=AV Club|access-date=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by Rhett Miller, Ken Bethea, Murry Hammond and Philip Peeples.\n#\"Jagged\" \u2013 3:27\n#\"Lonely Holiday\" \u2013 4:08\n#\"Oppenheimer\" \u2013 3:28\n#\"Indefinitely\" \u2013 3:41\n#\"What We Talk About\" \u2013 4:10\n#\"Crash on the Barrelhead\"  (vocals by [[Murry Hammond]]) \u2013 2:39\n#\"Murder (Or a Heart Attack)\" \u2013 3:41\n#\"Alone So Far\" \u2013 4:17\n#\"Busted Afternoon\" \u2013 3:11\n#\"19\" \u2013 3:41\n#\"Let the Idiot Speak\" \u2013 3:43\n#\"Valentine\" (vocals by [[Murry Hammond]]) \u2013 3:08\n\n==Personnel==\n;Old 97's\n*Ken Bethea \u2013 guitar\n*Murry Hammond \u2013 bass, vocals\n*[[Rhett Miller]] \u2013 vocals, guitar\n*Philip Peeples \u2013 drums, percussion\n\n;Additional personnel\n*Jon Rauhouse \u2013 steel on \"Jagged\", \"Lonely Holiday\" and \"Alone So Far\"\n*[[Jon Brion]] \u2013 Vox organ on \"Murder (Or a Heart Attack)\"\n*Andrew Williams \u2013 odds and ends\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Old 97's}}\n\n[[Category:Old 97's albums]]\n[[Category:1999 albums]]\n[[Category:Elektra Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=March 2009}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Fight Songs\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Old 97's]]\n| cover      = Old_97s-Fight_Songs.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = April 27, 1999\n| recorded   = Kingsway in [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]], United States\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country rock]], [[alternative country]]\n| length     = 46:45\n| label      = [[Elektra Records|Elektra]] / [[Warner Music Group|WEA]]\n| producer   = Andrew Williams\n| prev_title = [[Too Far to Care]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[Early Tracks (EP)|Early Tracks]] EP\n| next_year  = 2000\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/fight-songs-mw0000236827 |title=Fight Songs \u2013 Old 97's |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=February 16, 2012 |last=Johnson |first=Zac}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''\n| rev2Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/music/1999-04-23/521834/ |title=Old 97's: Fight Songs (Elektra) |work=[[The Austin Chronicle]] |date=April 23, 1999 |accessdate=October 5, 2